
Import required modules

import tkinter as tk
import subprocess

Define main window

root = tk.Tk()
root.title("Custom Microsoft Windows Installation")
root.geometry("600x400")

Define variables

current_script = tk.StringVar()
percent_complete = tk.DoubleVar()

Define functions

def run_script(script):
subprocess.call(["powershell.exe", script])

def start_installation():
run_script("script1.ps1")
current_script.set("Script 1")
percent_complete.set(10)
root.update()
run_script("script2.ps1")
current_script.set("Script 2")
percent_complete.set(20)
root.update()
run_script("script3.ps1")
current_script.set("Script 3")
percent_complete.set(30)
root.update()
# Repeat for remaining scripts

Define widgets

current_script_label = tk.Label(root, textvariable=current_script)
current_script_label.pack()

progress_bar = tk.ttk.Progressbar(root, orient="horizontal", length=400, mode="determinate", maximum=100, variable=percent_complete)
progress_bar.pack()

start_button = tk.Button(root, text="Start Installation", command=start_installation)
start_button.pack()

dancing_bear = tk.PhotoImage(file="dancing_bear.gif")
dancing_bear_label = tk.Label(root, image=dancing_bear)
dancing_bear_label.pack()

Start GUI


You can create the GUI by using the Tkinter library in Python. To create the GUI, you need to import the Tkinter library, define the main window (root), define variables to store the current running script and percentage of completion, define functions to run the PowerShell scripts, define widgets to display the current script, progress bar, start button, and dancing bear, and finally, start the GUI.

Here's an example script for creating the GUI for a custom Microsoft Windows installation:

import tkinter as tk
import subprocess

root = tk.Tk()
root.title("Custom Microsoft Windows Installation")
root.geometry("600x400")

current_script = tk.StringVar()
percent_complete = tk.DoubleVar()

def run_script(script):
    subprocess.call(["powershell.exe", script])

def start_installation():
    run_script("script1.ps1")
    current_script.set("Script 1")
    percent_complete.set(10)
    root.update()
    run_script("script2.ps1")
    current_script.set("Script 2")
    percent_complete.set(20)
    root.update()
    run_script("script3.ps1")
    current_script.set("Script 3")
    percent_complete.set(30)
    root.update()
    # Repeat for remaining scripts

current_script_label = tk.Label(root, textvariable=current_script)
current_script_label.pack()

progress_bar = tk.ttk.Progressbar(root, orient="horizontal", length=400, mode="determinate", maximum=100, variable=percent_complete)
progress_bar.pack()

start_button = tk.Button(root, text="Start Installation", command=start_installation)
start_button.pack()

dancing_bear = tk.PhotoImage(file="dancing_bear.gif")
dancing_bear_label = tk.Label(root, image=dancing_bear)
dancing_bear_label.pack()

root.mainloop()

Here are the variables you might need to change in the script based on your requirements:

root.title: This sets the title of the main window. You can change it to any string you want.
root.geometry: This sets the size of the main window. You can change it to any desired size.
run_script function: You need to change the list of script.ps1 files in the run_script function based on the PowerShell scripts you want to run.
dancing_bear: You need to change the file name of the dancing bear to match the name of your GIF file.
The number of times the run_script function is repeated in the start_installation function. The number of times it should be repeated depends on the number of scripts you want to run.


